File: platform/mcp-server/src/http-routes.ts lines 290-293. Current code:
```
sessionServer = await createMcpServer(state);
sessionServers.push(sessionServer);
await sessionServer.connect(transport);
return transport.handleRequest(req, { parsedBody: body });
```
If `connect(transport)` throws, `sessionServer` is already in `sessionServers` with no transport ID. The stale session sweeper (line 442-443) explicitly skips sessions without transport IDs, so the orphan is never cleaned up. Fix: wrap in try/catch:
```
try {
  sessionServer = await createMcpServer(state);
  sessionServers.push(sessionServer);
  await sessionServer.connect(transport);
  return transport.handleRequest(req, { parsedBody: body });
} catch (err) {
  removeSession();
  throw err;
}
```
The outer Bun.serve fetch handler will catch the re-thrown error and return a 500.

File: platform/cli/src/commands/build.ts lines 278-293. Current code:
```
let building = false;
const rebuild = async () => {
  if (building) return;  // <-- silently drops the change
  building = true;
  // ... build ...
  building = false;
};
```
Fix: add `let pendingRebuild = false;` and change the guard:
```
let building = false;
let pendingRebuild = false;
const rebuild = async () => {
  if (building) {
    pendingRebuild = true;
    return;
  }
  building = true;
  pendingRebuild = false;
  // ... existing build logic in try/catch ...
  building = false;
  if (pendingRebuild) {
    pendingRebuild = false;
    void rebuild();
  }
};
```
Make sure the `pendingRebuild` check and `void rebuild()` call are AFTER setting `building = false` (in the finally block or after the try/catch).

File: platform/cli/src/commands/logs.ts lines 49-61. Current code sets `offset = currentSize` on line 60 synchronously, but `createReadStream` delivers data asynchronously. Fix:
```
let reading = false;
let readRequested = false;
const readNewContent = (): void => {
  if (reading) {
    readRequested = true;
    return;
  }
  const currentSize = statSync(filePath).size;
  if (currentSize < offset) offset = 0;
  if (currentSize <= offset) return;
  reading = true;
  const stream = createReadStream(filePath, { start: offset, encoding: 'utf-8' });
  stream.on('data', (chunk: string | Buffer) => process.stdout.write(chunk));
  stream.on('end', () => {
    offset = currentSize;
    reading = false;
    if (readRequested) {
      readRequested = false;
      readNewContent();
    }
  });
  stream.on('error', () => {
    reading = false;
  });
};
```

File: platform/browser-extension/src/browser-commands.ts lines 528-531. Current code inside the func passed to chrome.scripting.executeScript:
```
if (clr) {
  input.value = '';
}
input.value = clr ? txt : input.value + txt;
```
The `input.value = ''` on line 529 is immediately overwritten by line 531 (`input.value = clr ? txt : ...`). No event is dispatched between the two assignments, so the empty-string assignment has zero observable effect. Remove the if block (lines 528-530), keeping only line 531. The result should be:
```
input.value = clr ? txt : input.value + txt;
```

File: platform/mcp-server/src/extension-protocol.ts, in the handleExtensionMessage function. After parsing the JSON and extracting `parsed.params`, add a guard before the method handlers (around line 375):
```
const rawParams = parsed.params;
if (rawParams !== undefined && rawParams !== null && (typeof rawParams !== 'object' || Array.isArray(rawParams))) {
  log.warn(`Dropping message with non-object params: ${method}`);
  return;
}
const params = rawParams as Record<string, unknown> | undefined;
```
Then use `params` in all the handler calls instead of `parsed.params as Record<string, unknown>`. This removes all the unsafe `as` casts and centralizes validation. The Array.isArray check is needed because `typeof [] === 'object'`.

File: platform/mcp-server/src/version-check.ts lines 52-72. The issue is in the comparison loop: when Number() returns NaN for a non-numeric segment, both `latestSegment > currentSegment` and `latestSegment < currentSegment` return false (NaN comparisons), so the loop continues to the next segment as if they were equal. Fix: after the `Number()` parse, treat NaN as 0 (the safest default — a malformed segment should not prevent the numeric segments from being compared correctly):
```
const parse = (v: string): number[] =>
  v.replace(/^v/, '').split('.').map(segment => {
    const hyphen = segment.indexOf('-');
    const n = Number(hyphen >= 0 ? segment.slice(0, hyphen) : segment);
    return Number.isFinite(n) ? n : 0;
  });
```
Add test cases in version-check.test.ts: `isNewer('1.0.abc', '2.0.0')` should be `true`, `isNewer('2.0.0', '1.0.abc')` should be `true` (2.0.0 > 1.0.0 when abc->0).
